Date: 12-08-2025

Aim
To model a product with price and a discounted variant.
To compute selling price as price × (1 − discountRate).
To validate discount rate and print result to two decimals.
Algorithm
Read price p (double) and discount rate d (double).
If d > 1, print "Not applicable" and exit.
Else compute sellingPrice = p * (1 - d).
Round to two decimals for display.
Print as "Rs. X" where X is formatted value.
Use inheritance: Product (price) and DiscountedProduct (discountRate).
End program.
Program (Java)
import java.util.*;
class Product {
    public double price;
    public Product(double price){ this.price = price; }
}
class DiscountedProduct extends Product {
    private double discountRate;
    public DiscountedProduct(double price, double discountRate){
        super(price);
        this.discountRate = discountRate;
    }
    public double calculateSellingPrice(){
        return price * (1 - discountRate);
    }
}
public class ProductDiscountApp {
    public static void main(String[] args){
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
        double p = Double.parseDouble(sc.nextLine().trim());
        double d = Double.parseDouble(sc.nextLine().trim());
        if (d > 1.0){
            System.out.println("Not applicable");
        } else {
            DiscountedProduct dp = new DiscountedProduct(p, d);
            System.out.printf("Rs. %.2f%n", dp.calculateSellingPrice());
        }
        sc.close();
    }
}


Sample Output
Input: 50.00 and 0.20
Output: Rs. 40.00
Result
Applied percentage discount correctly on base price.
Handled invalid discount rate (>1) with proper message.
